@database "VMem_Prefs"
@node Main "VMem Preferences Manual - Copyright (c)1994 By Lee Braiden"
        The VMem preferences program is added to your system in the "Prefs"
drawer of your boot disk. From this program, all features of the VMem package
can be controlled  by simply selecting the gadgets.

        When you run VMem,you will see a window with gadgets for the
following options:


        IMPORTANT : Read the @{"IMPORTANT NOTE" link Note } before going on.


        @{"Memory Emulation " link MemEmu}
        @{"Memory Options   " link ForceEmu}
        @{"Memory Limits    " link LowMemLimit}
        @{"Storage Options  " link Select}

        @{"Save             " link Save}
        @{"Use              " link Use}
        @{"Cancel           " link Cancel}
@endnode
@node MemEmu "The following memory emulation options are available:"
        @{"Chip     "   link ChipEmu}
        @{"Fast     "   link FastEmu}
        @{"Public   "   link PublicEmu}

        @{"Clear    "   link ClearEmu}
        @{"Reverse  "   link ReverseEmu}
@endnode

@node Note

        NOTES:

            *       Many of these options are for advanced users,and could
                    (and should) be ignored by novices.

            *       Help is available in the VMem Prefs program by pressing
                    the Help key, or clicking the right mouse button while
                    the mouse pointer is over a gadget.
@endnode

@node FastEmu



        Fast:           This option allows you to set the @{"FAST memory" link FASTMem}
                        emulation mode. Clicking the gadget (or Holding the
                        right Amiga-Key and pressing F) will toggle between
                        the following :

                            @{"FAST     " link FastEmuFAST}
                            @{"CHIP     " link FastEmuCHIP}
                            @{"PUBLIC   " link FastEmuPUBLIC}
@endnode
@node FastEmuFAST



                        FAST:           Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate FAST memory to use @{"FAST" link FASTMem}
                                        memory . (This is the normal mode)
@endnode
@node FastEmuCHIP



                        CHIP:           Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate FAST memory to use @{"CHIP" link CHIPMem}
                                        memory instead.
@endnode
@node FastEmuPUBLIC



                        PUBLIC:         Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate FAST memory to use @{"PUBLIC" link PUBLICMem}
                                        memory instead. (This is probably
                                        the best option for an Amiga without
                                        FAST memory installed.)
@endnode
@node ChipEmu



        Chip:           This option allows you to set the @{"CHIP memory" link CHIPMem}
                        emulation mode. Clicking the gadget (or Holding the
                        right Amiga-Key and pressing C) will toggle between
                        the following :

                            @{"CHIP     " link ChipEmuCHIP}
                            @{"FAST     " link ChipEmuFAST}
                            @{"PUBLIC   " link ChipEmuPUBLIC}
@endnode
@node ChipEmuFAST



                        FAST:           Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate CHIP memory to use @{"FAST" link FASTMEM}
                                        memory . (This is a very dangerous
                                        option - don't use unless you know
                                        what you're doing !)
@endnode
@node ChipEmuCHIP



                        CHIP:           Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate @{"CHIP memory" link CHIPMem} to use CHIP
                                        memory. (This is the normal mode -
                                        You should probably leave it alone.)
@endnode
@node ChipEmuPUBLIC



                        PUBLIC:         Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate CHIP memory to use @{"PUBLIC" link PUBLICMem}
                                        memory instead. (This is a very
                                        dangerous option - don't use unless
                                        you know what you're doing!)
@endnode
@node PublicEmu



        Public:         This option allows you to set the @{"PUBLIC memory" link PUBLICMem}
                        emulation mode. Clicking the gadget (or Holding the
                        right Amiga-Key and pressing P) will toggle between
                        the following :

                            @{"CHIP     " link PublicEmuCHIP}
                            @{"FAST     " link PublicEmuFAST}
                            @{"PUBLIC   " link PublicEmuPUBLIC}
@endnode
@node PublicEmuFAST



                        FAST:           Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate PUBLIC memory to use @{"FAST" link FASTMem}
                                        memory. (This is a dangerous option-
                                        don't use it unless you know what
                                        you're doing.)
@endnode
@node PublicEmuCHIP



                        CHIP:           Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate PUBLIC memory to use @{"CHIP" link CHIPMem}
                                        memory instead. (You probably
                                        shouldn't use this!)
@endnode
@node PublicEmuPUBLIC



                        PUBLIC:         Sets VMem to cause all attempts to
                                        allocate PUBLIC memory to use @{"PUBLIC" link PUBLICMem}
                                        memory. (This is the normal mode,and
                                        should probably be left alone.)
@endnode
@node ClearEmu



        Clear:          This gadget allows you to disable programs' requests
                        for @{"CLEAR memory" link CLEARMem}. (You should probably keep this
                        option at "CLEAR" ).
@endnode
@node ReverseEmu



        Reverse:        This is option allows you to disable programs'
                        requests for @{"REVERSE" link REVERSEMem} memory. (You should probably
                        keep this option at "REVERSE").
@endnode
@node ForceEmu



        Force:          This option allows you to force programs to allocate
                        @{"CLEAR" link CLEARMem} or @{"REVERSE" link REVERSEMem} memory even if they didn't ask for
                        it. (You should probably leave this at "No Force".)
                        (Programmers may find the "Clear" option handy for
                        debugging, but remember to leave it off to test your
                        program properly).
@endnode
@node LowMemLimit



        LowMemLimit:    This option allows you to set the minimum amount of
                        (real) memory to keep free. This should probably be
                        kept at about 50000 to allow the Amiga to display
                        messages,etc.
@endnode
@node Select



        Select:         This gadget will bring up a "Drawer Requester" with
                        which you can select the drawer where you want VMem
                        to store it's temporary files. The more this drawer
                        can hold,the more Virtual Memory you will have.
@endnode
@node Save



        Save:           Sets and Saves your current preferences, and quits.
@endnode
@node Use



        Use:            Just Sets (doesn't save) current preferences, and
                        quits.
@endnode
@node Cancel



        Cancel:         Resets preferences to previous settings, and quits.
@endnode
@node CHIPMem


        CHIP Memory:    This is the standard type of memory in an AMIGA.It
                        is used for programs,information,graphics,sound,and
                        any thing else the computer might need to store.This
                        is present in all AMIGAS.
@endnode
@node FASTMem


        FAST Memory:    This is the type of memory which on most memory
                        expansions. It CANNOT be used for graphics or sound.
@endnode
@node PUBLICMem


        PUBLIC Memory:  This is just means 'any memory available', although
                        when a program asks the computer for PUBLIC memory,
                        it will be given FAST memory if any is available.
                        (In other words, the computer gives a program CHIP
                        memory only as a last resort.)
@endnode
@node CLEARMem


        CLEAR Memory:   This is FAST *OR* CHIP memory which is set to zero
                        before a program gets it.
@endnode
@node REVERSEMem

        REVERSE Memory: If you don't know,you don't need to know.
@endnode
